06489nam a22011055i 9780691199870DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911998707 a10.1515/97806911998702doi  a(DE-B1597)539915  a(OCoLC)1138676958  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a975.5/552030922231 aTomlins, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn the Matter of Nat Turner :bA Speculative History /cChristopher Tomlins. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b10 b/w illus. 2 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPrologue. What’s Past? -- tPart I: Perpetually Thirsting -- tChapter 1. Confessions: Of Text and Paratext -- tChapter 2. Reading Luke in Southampton County -- tPart II: A Sword in the Sunlight -- tChapter 3. The Shudder of the Thought -- tChapter 4. The Work of Death: Massacre, Retribution -- tPart III: Glossolalia -- tChapter 5. On the Guilt of Fragile Sovereigns -- tChapter 6. Revulsions of Capital: Virginia, 1829–32 -- tEpilogue. Demonic Ambiguities -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA bold new interpretation of Nat Turner and the slave rebellion that stunned the American SouthIn 1831 Virginia, Nat Turner led a band of Southampton County slaves in a rebellion that killed fifty-five whites, mostly women and children. After more than two months in hiding, Turner was captured, and quickly convicted and executed. In the Matter of Nat Turner penetrates the historical caricature of Turner as befuddled mystic and self-styled Baptist preacher to recover the haunting persona of this legendary American slave rebel, telling of his self-discovery and the dawning of his Christian faith, of an impossible task given to him by God, and of redemptive violence and profane retribution.Much about Turner remains unknown. His extraordinary account of his life and rebellion, given in chains as he awaited trial in jail, was written down by an opportunistic white attorney and sold as a pamphlet to cash in on Turner’s notoriety. But the enigmatic rebel leader had an immediate and broad impact on the American South, and his rebellion remains one of the most momentous episodes in American history. Christopher Tomlins provides a luminous account of Turner's intellectual development, religious cosmology, and motivations, and offers an original and incisive analysis of the Turner Rebellion itself and its impact on Virginia politics. Tomlins also undertakes a deeply critical examination of William Styron’s 1967 novel, The Confessions of Nat Turner, which restored Turner to the American consciousness in the era of civil rights, black power, and urban riots.A speculative history that recovers Turner from the few shards of evidence we have about his life, In the Matter of Nat Turner is also a unique speculation about the meaning and uses of history itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  a100 Greatest African Americans.  aCarlo Ginzburg.  aCivil War history.  aCivil War.  aDavid F. Allmendinger Jr.  aDenmark Vesey.  aDred.  aExtraordinary Black Americans.  aFrederick Douglass.  aFrom Colonial to Contemporary Times.  aHarriet Beecher Stowe.  aHenry Box Brown.  aKyle Baker graphic novel.  aMolefi Kete Asante.  aNat Turner and the Rising in Southampton County.  aNat Turner in Jerusalem.  aNathan Alan Davis.  aPatrick H. Breen.  aScot French.  aSolomon Northup.  aSusan Altman.  aThe Birth of a Nation.  aThe Cheese and the Worms.  